When the `Tooltip` is controlled, the [onOpen](https://github.com/mui-org/material-ui/blob/v4.5.0/packages/material-ui/src/Tooltip/Tooltip.js#L194) and [onClose](https://github.com/mui-org/material-ui/blob/v4.5.0/packages/material-ui/src/Tooltip/Tooltip.js#L262) functions will still fire at the times when it would open/close the tooltip in the uncontrolled case. You can use these functions to change the controlled state of the `Tooltip`.

Working example:

```
import React from &quot;react&quot;;
import ReactDOM from &quot;react-dom&quot;;

import Tooltip from &quot;@material-ui/core/Tooltip&quot;;
import Button from &quot;@material-ui/core/Button&quot;;

function App() {
  const [tooltipIsOpen, setTooltipIsOpen] = React.useState(false);
  return (
    &lt;div className=&quot;App&quot;&gt;
      &lt;Tooltip
        open={tooltipIsOpen}
        onOpen={() =&gt; setTooltipIsOpen(true)}
        onClose={() =&gt; setTooltipIsOpen(false)}
        title=&quot;I&#39;m a controlled tooltip&quot;
      &gt;
        &lt;span&gt;Hover over me or click the button&lt;/span&gt;
      &lt;/Tooltip&gt;
      &lt;div style={{ marginTop: 50 }}&gt;
        &lt;Button
          onClick={() =&gt; setTooltipIsOpen(!tooltipIsOpen)}
          variant=&quot;contained&quot;
          color=&quot;primary&quot;
        &gt;
          Click me to {tooltipIsOpen ? &quot;close&quot; : &quot;open&quot;} the tooltip
        &lt;/Button&gt;
      &lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
  );
}

const rootElement = document.getElementById(&quot;root&quot;);
ReactDOM.render(&lt;App /&gt;, rootElement);
```

[![Edit controlled Tooltip](https://codesandbox.io/static/img/play-codesandbox.svg)](https://codesandbox.io/s/controlled-tooltip-19jrb?fontsize=14)

The way to understand this is to realize that the label&#39;s purpose is _not_ to tell the compiler which parameter this is. The order and type, combined with default values, does that.

The label&#39;s purpose is purely to dictate to the _caller_ what the caller must say.

So for example:

```
func f(p1 param1:String = &quot;one&quot;, p2 param2:Int = 2) {}

f(p1:&quot;hey&quot;, p2:42)
f(p1:&quot;hey&quot;)
f(p2:42)
f()
// but not:
// f(p2:42, p1:&quot;hey&quot;)
```

The label `p1:` does not mean, &quot;Hey, compiler, this is the `param1` parameter.&quot;

It means, &quot;Hey, caller, if you include this parameter (which must come first if you include both), you must label it `p1:`.&quot;

One thing not mentioned yet is for functions or initializers that have multiple parameters with defaults and you only want to override one or two of the defaults. For example:

    func foo(aString: String = &quot;&quot;, anInt: Int = 42, aFloat: Float = 10) {}

    foo(aFloat: 50) // Skip the params where you want to use the defaults.

    // some already existing component, you need to get it somehow
    // most likely via `import &lt;something-to-import&gt;`
    let theExternalComponent = {
      props: { wrap: { default: false, type: Boolean } },
      template: &quot;&lt;li&gt;wrap:{{wrap}}&lt;/li&gt;&quot;
    };
    // this simulates the global registration
    Vue.component(&quot;v-some-external-component&quot;, theExternalComponent);
    
    // -- lets start --
    
    // lets extend that component - and overwrite the default prop for wrap
    let extendedExternalwithOtherDefaults = {
      extends: theExternalComponent,
      mixins: [{ props: { wrap: { default: true } } }],
    };
    
    var app = new Vue({
      el: &quot;#app&quot;,
      components: { &quot;v-my-customized-component&quot;: extendedExternalwithOtherDefaults }
    });
   

html ([pug][1] actually but that does not matter here)
    
    div(id=&quot;app&quot;)
      ul
        v-some-external-component
    
        v-some-external-component(wrap)
    
        v-my-customized-component
        // now defaults to wrap:true
    
        v-my-customized-component(:wrap=&quot;false&quot;) 
        // you can still set the wrap to false if required

output

    wrap:false
    wrap:true
    wrap:true
    wrap:false

